In TypeScript, you can use the `as` keyword to explicitly cast a value to a specific type. This can be useful when you know that a value will always be of a certain type, even though the type system may not be able to infer this.

For example, if you have a function that returns a value of type `string | number`, but you know that it will only ever return a string, you can use the `as` keyword to cast the value to the `string` type:
```
function myFunction(): string | number {
  // ...
}

const myValue = myFunction() as string;
```
This will allow you to access the properties and methods of the `string` type on the `myValue` variable, even though the type system may not be able to infer that the variable is a string.

Keep in mind that using the `as` keyword to cast a value to a specific type can be risky if you are not absolutely certain that the value will always be of that type. If you cast a value to the wrong type, you may encounter runtime errors or unexpected behavior in your code.

